## Step 4: Calculate the energy of one photon.
$E = \frac{hc}{\lambda} = \frac{(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \mathrm{~J~s}) \times (3.00 \times 10^8 \mathrm{~m/s})}{3.00 \times 10^{-7} \mathrm{~m}} = 6.626 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{~J}$.

## Step 5: Calculate the energy of one mole of photons.
To find the energy of one mole of photons, we multiply the energy of one photon by Avogadro's number ($6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$). So, $E_{\mathrm{mole}} = (6.626 \times 10^{-19} \mathrm{~J}) \times (6.022 \times 10^{23} \mathrm{~mol}^{-1}) = 3.99 \times 10^5 \mathrm{~J/mol}$.

## Step 6: Convert the energy from Joules per mole to kiloJoules per mole.
$E_{\mathrm{mole}} = \frac{3.99 \times 10^5 \mathrm{~J/mol}}{1000} = 399 \mathrm{~kJ/mol}$.

## Step 7: Compare the calculated energy with the typical single-bond energy.
The energy of one mole of UV photons is $399 \mathrm{~kJ/mol}$, which is very close to the typical single-bond energy of $400 \mathrm{~kJ/mol}$.

